    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="26"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d26">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 835.001/38.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">Lorillard</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 332.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Buenos Aires</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-14">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 14, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to my telegram of August 9, with
                    respect to the death of President Roque Saenz Peña early that day, I have the
                        <pb facs="0138" n="22" xml:id="pg_22"/> honor to report that Doctor
                    Victorino de la Plaza, the Vice President, who has been acting as chief
                    executive for the past eleven months, has thereby become President of the
                    Argentine Republic for the remainder of the present term, which ends in 1916.
                    Sehor Benito Villanueva, the Vice President of the Senate, is next in succession
                    to the Presidency. * * *</p>
                <p>The members of the Legation attended the funeral with the rest of the diplomatic
                    body. The text of the telegrams of condolence from the President and Secretary
                    of State were given publicity.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">George Lorillard</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
